\[
12 \text{ seasons} \times 2 \text{ episodes per season} = 24 \text{ episodes lost}
\]

For the second series:
\[
14 \text{ seasons} \times 2 \text{ episodes per season} = 28 \text{ episodes lost}
\]

Next, we calculate the total number of episodes lost:

\[
24 \text{ episodes lost from the first series} + 28 \text{ episodes lost from the second series} = 52 \text{ episodes lost}
\]

Each season originally had 16 episodes, so we calculate the total number of episodes originally downloaded:

\[
12 \text{ seasons} \times 16 \text{ episodes per season} = 192 \text{ episodes}
\]
\[
14 \text{ seasons} \times 16 \text{ episodes per season} = 224 \text{ episodes}
\]

Adding the original total episodes gives:
\[
192 \text{ episodes} + 224 \text{ episodes} = 416 \text{ episodes}
\]

Finally, to find the remaining episodes after the loss:

\[
416 \text{ original episodes} - 52 \text{ lost episodes} = 364 \text{ remaining episodes}
\]

Thus, the number of episodes that remained after the computer's mechanical failure is:
\[
\boxed{364}
\] 
