Quinten sees three buildings downtown and decides to estimate their heights. He knows from a book on local buildings that the one in the middle is 100 feet tall. The one on the left looks like it is 80% of the height of the middle one. The one on the right looks 20 feet shorter than if the building on the left and middle were stacked on top of each other. How tall does Quinten estimate their total height to be? 
Response:
To estimate the total height of the three buildings, we will follow these steps:

1. Identify the height of each building.
2. Calculate the height of the middle building.
3. Determine the height of the building on the left.
4. Determine the height of the building on the right.
5. Sum the heights of all three buildings to get the total height.

First, we know that the middle building is 100 feet tall.

Next, we calculate the height of the building on the left. This building is 80% of the height of the middle building:
\[
\text{Height of the left building} = 0.8 \times 100 = 80 \text{ feet}
\]

Now, we determine the height of the building on the right. This building is 20 feet shorter than the combined height of the building on the left and the middle building:
\[
\text{Height of the right building} = 100 + 80 - 20 = 160 \text{ feet}
\]

Finally, we sum the heights of all three buildings to get the total height:
\[
\text{Total height} = 100 + 80 + 160 = 340 \text{ feet}
\]

Therefore, Quinten estimates the total height of the three buildings to be \boxed{340}. 
