A mountain range has 200 active volcanoes. In a particular year, 20% of the volcanoes exploded in the first two months, 40% of the remaining exploded by the half of the year, and at the end of the year, another 50% of the volcanoes that hadn't already erupted also exploded. How many mountains are still intact at the end of the year? 
Response:
To determine how many mountains are still intact at the end of the year, we need to follow the sequence of events and calculate the number of active volcanoes that exploded in each phase.

1. **Initial number of active volcanoes:** 200.

2. **First phase: 20% of volcanoes exploded in the first two months.**
   \[
   \text{Number of volcanoes that exploded in the first two months} = 20\% \times 200 = 0.2 \times 200 = 40
   \]
   \[
   \text{Number of volcanoes still active after the first two months} = 200 - 40 = 160
   \]

3. **Second phase: 40% of the remaining volcanoes exploded by the half of the year.**
   \[
   \text{Number of volcanoes that exploded by the half of the year} = 40\% \times 160 = 0.4 \times 160 = 64
   \]
   \[
   \text{Number of volcanoes still active after the half of the year} = 160 - 64 = 96
   \]

4. **Third phase: 50% of the remaining volcanoes exploded at the end of the year.**
   \[
   \text{Number of volcanoes that exploded at the end of the year} = 50\% \times 96 = 0.5 \times 96 = 48
   \]
   \[
   \text{Number of volcanoes still active at the end of the year} = 96 - 48 = 48
   \]

Thus, the number of mountains that are still intact at the end of the year is \(\boxed{48}\). 
