If 8 carpenters can make 50 chairs in 10 days, how many carpenters are needed to make 75 chairs in 10 days? 
Response:
To determine how many carpenters are needed to make 75 chairs in 10 days, we start by finding the rate at which the carpenters work. We know that 8 carpenters can make 50 chairs in 10 days. Therefore, the number of chairs produced per carpenter per day is:

\[
\frac{50 \text{ chairs}}{8 \text{ carpenters} \times 10 \text{ days}} = \frac{50}{80} = \frac{5}{8} \text{ chairs per carpenter per day}
\]

Next, we need to find the total number of chairs that can be produced by one carpenter in 10 days. Using the rate we just calculated:

\[
\frac{5}{8} \text{ chairs per carpenter per day} \times 10 \text{ days} = \frac{50}{8} = \frac{25}{4} \text{ chairs per carpenter}
\]

This means that one carpenter can make \(\frac{25}{4}\) chairs in 10 days. To find out how many carpenters are needed to make 75 chairs in 10 days, we set up the following equation:

\[
n \text{ carpenters} \times \frac{25}{4} \text{ chairs per carpenter} = 75 \text{ chairs}
\]

Solving for \(n\):

\[
n \times \frac{25}{4} = 75
\]
\[
n = 75 \times \frac{4}{25} = \frac{300}{25} = 12
\]

Therefore, the number of carpenters needed to make 75 chairs in 10 days is:

\[
\boxed{12}
\] 
