   - Each double window has 2 windows.
   - Each double window has 2 double windows downstairs, which means each double window has 2 multiple windows.
   - Therefore, each double window downstairs has \(4 \text{ panels} \times 2 \text{ times} = 8 \text{ panels}\).
   - Since there are 6 double windows downstairs, the total number of panels downstairs is \(6 \text{ double windows} \times 8 \text{ panels per double window} = 48 \text{ panels}\).

2. Calculate the number of glass panels in the upstairs windows:
   - Each single window has 1 window, so it has 4 glass panels.
   - Since there are 8 single windows upstairs, the total number of panels upstairs is \(8 \text{ single windows} \times 4 \text{ panels per window} = 32 \text{ panels}\).

3. Add the number of panels from the downstairs and the upstairs windows to get the total number of panels in the house:
   - The total number of panels is \(48 \text{ panels (downstairs)} + 32 \text{ panels (upstairs)} = 80 \text{ panels}\).

Therefore, the total number of glass panels in the whole house is \(\boxed{80}\). 
