1. Calculate the total number of squares of toilet paper Bill has.
2. Determine how many squares Bill uses per day.
3. Calculate the number of days his supply will last.

First, we calculate the total number of squares of toilet paper Bill has. Since he has 1000 rolls and each roll has 300 squares, we have:
\[ 1000 \times 300 = 300,000 \text{ squares} \]

Next, we determine how many squares Bill uses per day. Since he uses 5 squares each time he goes to the bathroom and he goes to the bathroom three times a day, we have:
\[ 5 \times 3 = 15 \text{ squares per day} \]

Now, we calculate how many days his supply of 300,000 squares will last. We divide the total number of squares by the number of squares used per day:
\[ 300,000 \div 15 = 20,000 \text{ days} \]

Therefore, Bill's toilet paper supply will last for \(\boxed{20000}\) days. 
